=========================================
🔥 std::function & std::bind (C++11)
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

=========================================
1. What is std::function?
=========================================

std::function is a type-erased wrapper that can store
ANY callable object.

Callable objects include:
✓ normal functions
✓ lambda functions
✓ functors (function objects)
✓ std::bind expressions

Header:
#include <functional>

-----------------------------------------

2. Basic Example

#include <iostream>
#include <functional>
using namespace std;

int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {

    std::function<int(int,int)> f;

    f = add;   // function pointer

    cout << f(2, 3);
}

Output:
5

-----------------------------------------

3. std::function with Lambda

std::function<int(int,int)> f = [](int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
};

-----------------------------------------

4. std::function with Functor

struct Multiply {
    int operator()(int a, int b) {
        return a * b;
    }
};

std::function<int(int,int)> f = Multiply();

-----------------------------------------

5. Why use std::function?

Advantages:
✓ Can store ANY callable type
✓ Useful for callbacks
✓ Used in STL algorithms and APIs
✓ Runtime polymorphism for functions

-----------------------------------------

6. std::function overhead

Disadvantages:
✗ Slight performance overhead (type erasure)
✗ Slower than direct function calls
✗ Uses heap in some cases

-----------------------------------------

7. Real Use Cases

✓ Callbacks
✓ Event handlers
✓ Strategy pattern
✓ STL algorithms (rare usage)
✓ Thread functions

-----------------------------------------
=========================================
🔥 std::bind
=========================================

=========================================
8. What is std::bind?
=========================================

std::bind is used to:
👉 fix (bind) arguments of a function
👉 create a new callable object

It allows partial function application.

-----------------------------------------

9. Basic Example

#include <iostream>
#include <functional>
using namespace std;

int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {

    auto f = std::bind(add, 10, 20);

    cout << f();
}

Output:
30

-----------------------------------------

10. Placeholder Concept

#include <iostream>
#include <functional>
using namespace std;

int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {

    auto f = std::bind(add, std::placeholders::_1, 10);

    cout << f(5);   // 5 + 10
}

Output:
15

-----------------------------------------

11. std::bind with Class Member Function

#include <iostream>
#include <functional>
using namespace std;

class Test {
public:
    void print(int x) {
        cout << x;
    }
};

int main() {

    Test t;

    auto f = std::bind(&Test::print, &t, std::placeholders::_1);

    f(100);
}

Output:
100

-----------------------------------------

12. Why std::bind is used?

Use cases:
✓ Callback adaptation
✓ Fixing arguments
✓ Converting functions to required signature

-----------------------------------------

13. std::bind drawbacks (IMPORTANT)

✗ Hard to read
✗ Error-prone
✗ Replaced by lambdas in modern C++

Modern C++ prefers:
👉 Lambdas instead of bind

Example:

auto f = [](int x) { return add(x, 10); };

-----------------------------------------
=========================================
14. std::function vs std::bind vs lambda
=========================================

Lambda:
✓ Best modern choice
✓ Fast
✓ Readable

std::function:
✓ Stores callable objects
✓ Good for APIs/callbacks

std::bind:
✗ Older approach
✗ Mostly replaced by lambda

-----------------------------------------
=========================================
15. Interview Answer
=========================================

Q: What is std::function?

A:
std::function is a type-erased wrapper that can store and invoke any callable object like functions, lambdas, functors, or bind expressions.

-----------------------------------------

Q: What is std::bind?

A:
std::bind is used to create a new callable by binding arguments of an existing function.

-----------------------------------------
=========================================
ONE-LINE REVISION
=========================================

std::function = universal callable wrapper

std::bind = argument fixer (creates new function)

Modern C++ prefers lambda over std::bind
